\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf1 MORE COMPLEX THEMATIC CONCEPTS: Psychology, Literature/Art, Culture, Philosophy}
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl264\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Zizek\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s book on Hegel dives into a number of ideas for psychological, literary, cultural and philosophical themes that could be interesting to weave into the story. }
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The idea of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Enclosure\u8221\'94 resonates with the history of capitalism, of course, and has some obvious thematic weight along the lines of reading a story about a set of characters who are, more or less, invented/controlled by unseen observers.  The story itself kind of breaks down  the 4}{\f0\fs18\b0\i0\super\cf1 th}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  wall \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  of authorship (who is telling/directing this story?), what is the role of the audience \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  as well as playing around with the structure of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93god/maker\u8221\'94 video games (can I, the player, reach a level where I can help to direct the course of the game?).}
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 In terms of literary antecedents, these concepts resonate especially with works by Brecht and, to some extent, Kafka. In the same way the KS Robinson acknowledges his debt to Bogdanov, perhaps I can nod to Brecht and Kafka. And speaking of Bogdanov (and KS Robinson) I owe them a great debt of gratitude as well. Read up on the Proletcult stuff.  Re-read the piece in e-flux about cops and art.  Think about all the things I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve tried to say in eRepublik via \u8220\'93PQ\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93RFW\u8221\'94 about d\u233\'E9tourning the game and see how I might incorporate that. For that matter, why not introduce PQ himself as a character?}
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The Lands of Saskantinon play with post-apocalyptic genres, situating itself in the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93zookeeper\u8221\'94 kind of style. Humanity (and other sentient life on Earth) is saved (from the \u8220\'93Flood\u8221\'94, canonically speaking, that is, the ecocide) only through the benevolent oversight of a \u8220\'93big Other\u8221\'94 (the Agency). But that is also when it gets interesting.  The Heliops fear the big Other, while denying that it actually exists and creating a symbolic appearance (}{\f1\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 petit objet a}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 ) where the impossible resides, using the most obvious metaphor of all, the literal \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93big Other\u8221\'94 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  the Sun.  The variety of \u8220\'93stargazers\u8221\'94 are more Kantian \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  understanding the \u8220\'93gap\u8221\'94 in noumenal terms, that it is something \u8220\'93out there\u8221\'94, which is fundamentally not part of phenomena as we know it, something \u8220\'93else\u8221\'94, mysteriously \u8220\'93other\u8221\'94, to be \u8220\'93believed in\u8221\'94, perhaps \u8220\'93on faith alone\u8221\'94, etc.  The twist is, of course, that the \u8220\'93big Other\u8221\'94 is \u8220\'93real\u8221\'94 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  in the sense that it does actually exist \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  but (ha-ha, surprise double-twist) they are rather incompetent and themselves filled with contradiction. }
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Our Saskan Hegelians, Derridadaists and Badiouamaticians express varieties of understanding the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93not-all\u8221\'94 of the Enclosure in more materialist terms:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Hegelians as a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93twist\u8221\'94 that will reveal the benevolent nature of the Universe, }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Derridadaists: as a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93difference\u8221\'94 that reflects our own sentient split, possibly illusionary, between subject and object, a}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Badioumaticians: as the harbinger of an \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93event\u8221\'94 that will change everything in the blink of an eye, }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85and so on and so forth.}
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 His thoughts on the development of western music are also intriguing. This might help to flesh out the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93bard song\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93song cycle\u8221\'94 thematic elements, colors of the story.    }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Likewise, multiple references to jokes, iconic performances would certainly be in order if I wanted to acknowledge Zizek his own bad self as an influence... }
\par\plain \f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 How to work this stuff into my work methods?  Let\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s try adding some stuff to character and scene templates as reminders along these lines? }
